00:11:45,020 --> 00:11:45,620
whatever,

294
00:11:45,620 --> 00:11:46,540
however it's given,

295
00:11:46,540 --> 00:11:47,660
the way it's presented

296
00:11:47,660 --> 00:11:48,140
to you,

297
00:11:48,140 --> 00:11:50,810
transform the metric to the new

298
00:11:50,810 --> 00:11:53,480
coordinate system that you have constructed,

299
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:55,380
calculate

300
00:11:55,380 --> 00:11:56,280
the new metric,

301
00:11:56,280 --> 00:11:59,640
and ask whether it looks like a flat metric.

302
00:12:00,220 --> 00:12:01,540
Now of course,

303
00:12:01,540 --> 00:12:04,880
that will take an infinite amount of time,

304
00:12:04,880 --> 00:12:05,980
you'll never get there,

305
00:12:05,980 --> 00:12:06,960
so

306
00:12:06,960 --> 00:12:07,780
you need a better technique.

307
00:12:08,980 --> 00:12:11,480
And the better technique is

308
00:12:11,480 --> 00:12:13,980
to search for diagnostic quantities.

309
00:12:15,020 --> 00:12:16,180
Quantities which…

310
00:12:16,880 --> 00:12:19,040
…which are built out of the metric,

311
00:12:19,040 --> 00:12:21,660
the metric and its derivatives and so forth,

312
00:12:21,660 --> 00:12:22,500
things

313
00:12:22,500 --> 00:12:23,520
that you can calculate,

314
00:12:23,520 --> 00:12:24,600
which,

315
00:12:24,600 --> 00:12:28,940
if they are zero everywheres throughout the space,

316
00:12:28,940 --> 00:12:29,800
that

317
00:12:29,800 --> 00:12:30,880
says the space is flat.

318
00:12:32,320 --> 00:12:34,480
If they're non-zero anyplace,

319
00:12:34,480 --> 00:12:36,920
it says that the space is curved there.

320
00:12:37,560 --> 00:12:40,170
The diagnostic quantity that does

321
00:12:40,170 --> 00:12:42,780
that is called the curvature tensor.

322
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:46,140
Today's goal is to get to the…

323
00:12:46,180 --> 00:12:50,480
…the curvature tensor of a Riemannian geometry.

324
00:12:53,120 --> 00:12:54,660
And it's a complicated goal,

325
00:12:54,660 --> 00:12:55,220
I warn you.

326
00:12:55,860 --> 00:12:58,560
You've got to pay attention or else you'll fall asleep.

327
00:13:00,120 --> 00:13:04,700
This is a very soporific subject.

328
00:13:05,900 --> 00:13:07,970
I'll try from time to time to tell

329
00:13:07,970 --> 00:13:10,040
a joke or whatever to keep you awake.

330
00:13:11,120 --> 00:13:12,300
But on the other hand,

331
00:13:12,300 --> 00:13:14,180
if you can follow it,

332
00:13:14,180 --> 00:13:14,880
you've learned a lot.

333
00:13:14,880 --> 00:13:16,440
And it is very interesting.

334
00:13:16,640 --> 00:13:18,120
I think you'll find it very interesting.

335
00:13:18,220 --> 00:13:20,020
I'll try not to make it too boring.

336
00:13:20,880 --> 00:13:21,360
Okay.

337
00:13:27,800 --> 00:13:30,920
I told my friend Barack Obama never to apologize,

338
00:13:30,920 --> 00:13:33,100
and here I am apologizing already for being

339
00:13:33,100 --> 00:13:33,440
boring.

340
00:13:34,720 --> 00:13:35,200
Okay.

341
00:13:37,060 --> 00:13:38,220
What do we start with?

342
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:41,360
We start with a space.

343
00:13:41,620 --> 00:13:42,620
And a space means,

344
00:13:42,620 --> 00:13:43,540
first of all,

345
00:13:43,540 --> 00:13:44,860
a non-zero.

346
00:13:44,880 --> 00:13:45,640
Number of dimensions.

347
00:13:46,600 --> 00:13:48,620
The number of dimensions in

348
00:13:48,620 --> 00:13:50,640
Riemannian geometry can be anything.

349
00:13:52,160 --> 00:13:54,980
In principle you can even have a zero-dimensional space,

350
00:13:54,980 --> 00:13:56,320
but that's pretty damn boring.

351
00:13:56,420 --> 00:13:57,120
It's just a point.

352
00:13:57,660 --> 00:13:59,720
A one-dimensional space is either an

353
00:13:59,720 --> 00:14:01,780
infinite line or a closed curve.

354
00:14:03,720 --> 00:14:05,280
If it's a closed curve,

355
00:14:05,280 --> 00:14:06,980
what is it characterized by?

356
00:14:07,060 --> 00:14:08,980
It's characterized by only one thing.

357
00:14:09,160 --> 00:14:11,080
The total length of the curve.

358
00:14:11,560 --> 00:14:14,500
Every curve is equivalent to every other curve.

359
00:14:14,500 --> 00:14:14,600
But the total length is not equal

360
00:14:14,600 --> 00:14:14,700
to the total length of the curve.

361
00:14:14,740 --> 00:14:15,460
The total length is equal to

362
00:14:15,460 --> 00:14:16,180
the total length of the curve.

363
00:14:16,280 --> 00:14:19,440
So if you have a piece

364
00:14:19,440 --> 00:14:22,600
of rope that closes on itself,

365
00:14:22,600 --> 00:14:23,760
that has a certain length,

366
00:14:23,760 --> 00:14:24,220
and

367
00:14:24,220 --> 00:14:26,180
wiggle it in any kinds of ways,

368
00:14:26,180 --> 00:14:27,860
or curve it in any kind of way,

369
00:14:27,860 --> 00:14:32,020
it can always be mapped

370
00:14:32,020 --> 00:14:36,240
or put on top of another piece of rope

371
00:14:36,240 --> 00:14:40,460
of exactly the same length in a precise way without

372
00:14:40,460 --> 00:14:41,160
stretching it.

373
00:14:41,340 --> 00:14:41,920
The only thing that's really important is that

374
00:14:41,920 --> 00:14:42,500
you're not going to have to make a single

375
00:14:42,500 --> 00:14:42,740
one-dimensional space.

376
00:14:42,740 --> 00:14:43,800
All the other one-dimensional spaces

377
00:14:43,800 --> 00:14:44,860
are all equivalent to each other,

378
00:14:44,860 --> 00:14:45,440
not quite.

379
00:14:45,940 --> 00:14:48,000
They're characterized only by their length.

380
00:14:48,060 --> 00:14:50,100
They're either infinite or they have a length l,

381
00:14:50,100 --> 00:14:52,880
and every one of them have given length

382
00:14:52,880 --> 00:14:55,280
l as identical to every

383
00:14:55,280 --> 00:14:57,680
other one in its intrinsic properties.

384
00:14:58,820 --> 00:15:02,520
A bug walking along a little piece of

385
00:15:02,520 --> 00:15:06,220
rope cannot distinguish one geometry from the other

386
00:15:06,220 --> 00:15:06,660
geometry.

387
00:15:06,820 --> 00:15:08,590
All it can do is count the number of

388
00:15:08,590 --> 00:15:10,360
steps that it takes them to go around the rope.

389
00:15:10,440 --> 00:15:11,420
It leaves a marker someplace.

390
00:15:11,900 --> 00:15:12,720
It goes around.

391
00:15:12,740 --> 00:15:13,540
It goes around the rope until

392
00:15:13,540 --> 00:15:14,340
it comes back to the marker.

393
00:15:14,460 --> 00:15:15,300
It counts the number of steps,

394
00:15:15,300 --> 00:15:16,980
and that's the only thing about that space.

395
00:15:17,720 --> 00:15:22,000
Two-dimensional spaces begin to become more complicated.

396
00:15:23,820 --> 00:15:24,880
There are flat ones.

397
00:15:25,120 --> 00:15:26,140
There are curved ones.

398
00:15:26,320 --> 00:15:27,240
A flat one is a plane.

399
00:15:27,640 --> 00:15:29,380
A curved one could be a sphere.

400
00:15:29,600 --> 00:15:31,980
It could be just a space with lumps,

401
00:15:31,980 --> 00:15:33,180
the surface of the earth,

402
00:15:33,180 --> 00:15:35,020
including the mountains and

403
00:15:35,020 --> 00:15:36,060
the valleys and so forth.

404
00:15:36,760 --> 00:15:39,260
It can even have weird topology,

405
00:15:39,260 --> 00:15:41,280
the surface of a doughnut,

406
00:15:41,280 --> 00:15:42,480
a torus.

407
00:15:42,740 --> 00:15:45,580
Or you can poke another hole in the torus

408
00:15:45,580 --> 00:15:48,420
and make a torus with two holes and so forth.

409
00:15:48,920 --> 00:15:51,100
So by the time you get to two-dimensional spaces,

410
00:15:51,100 --> 00:15:52,520
they're pretty complicated.

411
00:15:56,900 --> 00:15:57,440
Nevertheless,

412
00:15:57,440 --> 00:16:01,120
they are characterized by the metric tensor.

413
00:16:02,160 --> 00:16:05,680
And the question of whether they're flat is a computation,

414
00:16:05,680 --> 00:16:07,180
or as a first question,

415
00:16:07,180 --> 00:16:07,560
find

416
00:16:07,560 --> 00:16:10,120
something which distinguishes whether they're flat.

417
00:16:10,260 --> 00:16:11,300
Find a quantity.

418
00:16:11,960 --> 00:16:12,720
G-minus.

419
00:16:12,740 --> 00:16:12,900
If g-minu,

420
00:16:12,900 --> 00:16:16,300
g-m-n,

421
00:16:16,300 --> 00:16:17,480
the metric tensor,

422
00:16:17,480 --> 00:16:25,240
if it is not equal to zero,

423
00:16:25,240 --> 00:16:26,940
that does not mean the

424
00:16:26,940 --> 00:16:27,780
space is not flat.

425
00:16:27,960 --> 00:16:29,980
It just means you may be in the wrong coordinates.

426
00:16:30,540 --> 00:16:33,320
So you can't diagnose the space by

427
00:16:33,320 --> 00:16:36,100
asking whether g-m-n is zero or not.

428
00:16:36,480 --> 00:16:38,240
You want to find a quantity.

429
00:16:38,940 --> 00:16:40,520
Let us call it r.

430
00:16:41,600 --> 00:16:42,600
At the moment,

431
00:16:42,600 --> 00:16:43,780
I'm not going to tell

432
00:16:43,780 --> 00:16:44,960
you how many indices it has.

433
00:16:45,980 --> 00:16:47,020
Some quantity.

434
00:16:47,780 --> 00:16:49,500
Best it should be a tensor.

435
00:16:50,020 --> 00:16:53,260
Because if it's a tensor and it's non-zero,

436
00:16:53,260 --> 00:16:55,880
it's non-zero in every frame of reference.

437
00:16:56,760 --> 00:16:59,080
We'd like to find some quantity called r.

438
00:16:59,200 --> 00:17:00,300
R stands for Riemann,

439
00:17:00,300 --> 00:17:01,000
incidentally.

440
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:02,610
Riemann was the first person who

441
00:17:02,610 --> 00:17:04,220
asked this question and answered it.

442
00:17:05,119 --> 00:17:05,640
Uh...

443
00:17:07,339 --> 00:17:10,420
We want to find a thing called Riemann.

444
00:17:10,440 --> 00:17:10,500
Riemann.

445
00:17:10,520 --> 00:17:10,540
Riemann.

446
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:11,960
Such that,

447
00:17:11,960 --> 00:17:14,599
if Riemann is equal to zero,

448
00:17:14,599 --> 00:17:26,060
that implies that the space is flat and that there

449
00:17:26,060 --> 00:17:30,440
exist coordinates such that...

450
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:31,380
Sorry,

451
00:17:31,380 --> 00:17:33,120
did I say g-m-n not equal to zero?

452
00:17:33,700 --> 00:17:37,360
I mean not equal to delta m-n.

453
00:17:39,520 --> 00:17:40,500
g-m-n is equal to zero.

454
00:17:40,500 --> 00:17:42,260
is an interesting space.

455
00:17:42,260 --> 00:17:45,120
It's not very big.

456
00:17:45,120 --> 00:17:47,300
Yeah,

457
00:17:47,300 --> 00:17:49,400
GMN equals delta MN is what I meant.

458
00:17:53,140 --> 00:17:54,580
And that's what we're going to search for.

459
00:17:54,580 --> 00:17:56,780
The curvature tensor.

460
00:17:56,780 --> 00:17:58,240
It is a tensor.

461
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:02,250
Let me just remind you about a few properties

462
00:18:02,250 --> 00:18:04,660
of the metric tensor and what you do with it.

463
00:18:05,699 --> 00:18:06,880
First of all,

464
00:18:06,880 --> 00:18:09,350
GMN is by definition the thing

465
00:18:09,350 --> 00:18:11,820
that's a function of position in general.

466
00:18:12,140 --> 00:18:14,100
If it were not a function of position,

467
00:18:14,100 --> 00:18:14,980
incidentally,

468
00:18:14,980 --> 00:18:17,260
if it was a constant matrix,

469
00:18:17,260 --> 00:18:19,640
a constant set of coefficients,

470
00:18:20,100 --> 00:18:23,400
then it's very easy to find

471
00:18:23,400 --> 00:18:26,700
coordinates in which GMN is delta MN.

472
00:18:26,780 --> 00:18:28,580
You simply have to straighten out the angles.

473
00:18:28,580 --> 00:18:33,260
So if GMN is not dependent on position,

474
00:18:33,440 --> 00:18:34,040
then it's very easy to find

475
00:18:34,040 --> 00:18:34,640
coordinates in which GMN is delta MN.

476
00:18:34,660 --> 00:18:36,280
If it's just a set of coefficients,

477
00:18:36,280 --> 00:18:37,660
a set of numerical coefficients,

478
00:18:37,660 --> 00:18:39,160
then the space is definitely flat.

479
00:18:40,400 --> 00:18:40,880
Alright,

480
00:18:40,880 --> 00:18:42,870
so GMN is the metric tensor

481
00:18:42,870 --> 00:18:44,860
and what do you do with it?

482
00:18:45,060 --> 00:18:47,100
You take a little differential distance,

483
00:18:47,100 --> 00:18:48,240
dxM,

484
00:18:48,240 --> 00:18:50,080
multiply it by dxN.

485
00:18:50,280 --> 00:18:51,720
Here's your little differential displacement.

486
00:18:52,740 --> 00:18:55,250
It's characterized by a

487
00:18:55,250 --> 00:18:57,760
set of differential coordinate shifts,

488
00:18:57,760 --> 00:18:58,820
dxM,

489
00:18:58,820 --> 00:18:59,760
dxN.

490
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:01,650
You multiply them together and that

491
00:19:01,650 --> 00:19:03,300
gives you the square of the length

492
00:19:03,300 --> 00:19:06,470
between the tail and the arrow

493
00:19:06,470 --> 00:19:09,640
and the head of the vector.

494
00:19:09,980 --> 00:19:12,520
That's equal to ds squared.

495
00:19:13,100 --> 00:19:15,260
S standing for spatial distance,

496
00:19:15,260 --> 00:19:15,820
I suppose.

497
00:19:18,050 --> 00:19:18,380
Alright,

498
00:19:18,380 --> 00:19:18,660
now,

499
00:19:18,660 --> 00:19:20,840
the metric tensor is a tensor.

500
00:19:21,140 --> 00:19:23,040
I think we proved that last time.

501
00:19:23,320 --> 00:19:25,380
And the way you see that

502
00:19:25,380 --> 00:19:27,440
is just by saying ds squared,

503
00:19:27,440 --> 00:19:30,560
that's an invariant quantity.

504
00:19:30,740 --> 00:19:33,280
All coordinates are invariant.

505
00:19:33,280 --> 00:19:35,580
Let's call them coordinate systems.

506
00:19:36,160 --> 00:19:38,470
All coordinate systems should agree about

507
00:19:38,470 --> 00:19:40,780
the length of a given little vector.

508
00:19:41,660 --> 00:19:44,810
And if we take that same ds squared and

509
00:19:44,810 --> 00:19:47,960
write it in y coordinates instead of x coordinates,

510
00:19:48,680 --> 00:19:50,520
the length has to be the same.

511
00:19:50,740 --> 00:19:53,610
And that's sufficient to prove that GMN really is

512
00:19:53,610 --> 00:19:56,480
a tensor and that it transforms like a tensor.

513
00:19:58,560 --> 00:19:59,160
Okay,

514
00:19:59,160 --> 00:20:01,360
next property of GMN is it has an inverse.

515
00:20:03,080 --> 00:20:04,340
GMN is a matrix.

516
00:20:04,720 --> 00:20:07,520
It's a matrix and it has an inverse.

517
00:20:08,900 --> 00:20:12,140
The inverse satisfies the following equation.

518
00:20:13,959 --> 00:20:14,639
G,

519
00:20:14,639 --> 00:20:17,160
it's written again as a matrix.

520
00:20:17,280 --> 00:20:18,460
When I say it has an inverse,

521
00:20:18,460 --> 00:20:21,440
I mean it has an inverse as a matrix.

522
00:20:23,959 --> 00:20:27,060
GMN is a matrix with entries.

523
00:20:30,080 --> 00:20:30,760
And...

524
00:20:31,360 --> 00:20:32,940
It has an inverse.

525
00:20:34,220 --> 00:20:34,740
GMN,

526
00:20:34,740 --> 00:20:37,760
which is written with upper indices.

527
00:20:38,020 --> 00:20:38,320
They are,

528
00:20:38,320 --> 00:20:38,900
in fact,

529
00:20:38,900 --> 00:20:40,000
contravariant indices.

530
00:20:40,700 --> 00:20:43,740
And the properties of GMN with upper indices

531
00:20:43,740 --> 00:20:46,780
are such that if you multiply it by G,

532
00:20:46,780 --> 00:20:48,340
let's call it nr,

533
00:20:50,120 --> 00:20:51,420
and sum over n,

534
00:20:51,420 --> 00:20:54,820
but I don't have to sum over n because Einstein tells me that

535
00:20:54,820 --> 00:20:58,220
an upper and a lower index like this are automatically to be summed over.

536
00:20:59,160 --> 00:21:00,100
This is the sum.

537
00:21:00,100 --> 00:21:05,340
This actually corresponds to taking the matrix

538
00:21:05,340 --> 00:21:10,580
GMN and multiplying it by the matrix Gnr.

539
00:21:11,280 --> 00:21:14,360
And the resulting matrix is the unit matrix.

540
00:21:14,740 --> 00:21:15,020
Why?

541
00:21:15,200 --> 00:21:17,500
Because I told you that GMN is

542
00:21:17,500 --> 00:21:19,800
the inverse matrix to this one here.

543
00:21:20,180 --> 00:21:23,540
And the product then is the identity matrix.

544
00:21:23,820 --> 00:21:26,740
And the identity matrix is the Kronecker delta.

545
00:21:27,060 --> 00:21:29,720
And the Kronecker delta in general relativity,

546
00:21:29,720 --> 00:21:31,060
or in Riemannian geometry,

547
00:21:31,720 --> 00:21:34,070
is always written as a thing with

548
00:21:34,070 --> 00:21:36,420
one upper index and one lower index.

549
00:21:39,540 --> 00:21:41,960
At least if it's being treated as a tensor.

550
00:21:42,480 --> 00:21:43,660
The Kronecker delta,

551
00:21:43,660 --> 00:21:44,840
this is a thing to prove.

552
00:21:45,520 --> 00:21:47,840
Prove that if you take the Kronecker delta,

553
00:21:48,560 --> 00:21:50,920
and you transform it pretending it's a tensor,

554
00:21:51,160 --> 00:21:53,360
you just get back the Kronecker delta again.

555
00:21:53,620 --> 00:21:54,880
That's a thing that you can prove.

556
00:21:56,620 --> 00:21:57,180
So,

557
00:21:57,180 --> 00:21:58,360
these are tensor equations.

558
00:21:59,720 --> 00:22:02,430
This is the meaning of saying the

559
00:22:02,430 --> 00:22:05,140
GMN is the inverse matrix of Gnr.

560
00:22:06,880 --> 00:22:09,700
And once you have that...

561
00:22:09,700 --> 00:22:10,700
Oh,

562
00:22:10,700 --> 00:22:12,160
there's another thing that is important.

563
00:22:12,700 --> 00:22:14,300
In Riemannian geometry,

564
00:22:14,300 --> 00:22:16,940
as opposed to Einsteinian geometry,

565
00:22:17,460 --> 00:22:18,980
in Riemannian geometry,

566
00:22:18,980 --> 00:22:21,500
all lengths are positive.

567
00:22:22,720 --> 00:22:24,640
All lengths are positive.

568
00:22:25,400 --> 00:22:27,540
Or the squares of all lengths.

569
00:22:27,600 --> 00:22:28,100
More importantly,

570
00:22:28,100 --> 00:22:29,700
the squares of all lengths are positive.

571
00:22:30,440 --> 00:22:32,620
And all lengths are also positive.

572
00:22:32,900 --> 00:22:34,900
But the squares of all lengths are positive.

573
00:22:35,240 --> 00:22:37,020
And that says something about

574
00:22:37,020 --> 00:22:38,800
the properties of the metric tensor.

575
00:22:39,620 --> 00:22:42,570
What it says is that

576
00:22:42,570 --> 00:22:45,520
